That depends on what you mean by power and losing their soul.

If by power you mean authority, wealth, influence, military force, charisma, or knowledge, then history suggests that power doesn’t so much corrupt as amplify what is already there and expose weaknesses that were easier to ignore when the stakes were lower.

“Losing your soul” could mean several things:

* sacrificing your principles for expediency,
* becoming unable to empathize,
* treating people only as means to an end,
* becoming addicted to status or control,
* forgetting who you intended to become.

In that sense, the people who can withstand the most power tend to share a few characteristics:

* Humility: They recognize they can be wrong.
* Self-awareness: They notice when ambition, fear, or ego begins steering them.
* Strong principles: They have values that don’t change every time incentives do.
* Accountability: They invite honest criticism instead of surrounding themselves with yes-men.
* Purpose beyond themselves: Their identity isn’t built solely on possessing power.

An old observation captures this well:

Character is revealed when no one can stop you.

Power removes constraints. If no one can tell you “no,” your own character becomes the primary limit on your behavior.

There’s also a paradox:

The people most capable of handling great power are often the ones least attached to having it. They can relinquish it if keeping it would require betraying what they believe is right.

So the question may not be, “Who can withstand more power?”

It may be:

Who can continue seeking truth even when power rewards comforting illusions?

That’s a much harder test, because it asks whether you’ll let reality correct you when it costs you status, influence, or victory.

Whether anyone passes that test perfectly is doubtful. Most people need habits, trusted advisors, and institutions that help them stay grounded. Power can be held more safely when it is balanced by accountability rather than relying solely on personal virtue.